ve afforded to send us to the expensive private prep schools in our area. The public schools were not terrible, but they didn't offer the kind of high quality education experience that has enriched my life. &#10;The key ingredient of any child's success, be it in public, private, or home education, is parental involvement. Happily, many home schooled children do not lack such focus. &#10;The unspoken assumptions of many commentators reveal a knee jerk bias toward systematic public education, as if the benefits of such a system spoke for themselves. My home schooling parents were wise to make the choice that worked best for my family. I am grateful that they were free to make that choice. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="982" language="en" documentId="155" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Epicurus0" date="7/29/2013 10:46 PM GMT+0200" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://www.washingtonpost.com/local/students-home-schooling-highlights-debate-over-va-religious-exemption-law/2013/07/28/ee2dbb1a-efbc-11e2-bed3-b9b6fe264871_comment.html?commentID=washingtonpost.com/ECHO/item/1375130818-497-310" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="155" notes="" title="Student’s home-schooling highlights debate over Va. religious exemption law"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="111"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="112" end="500"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="501" end="675"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="676" end="982"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51"/></xmi:XMI>